column5: ['Fewer than 76,000', 'Between 76,000 and 88,000, inclusive', 'More than 88,000 but fewer than 100,000', 'Between 100,000 and 112,000, inclusive', 'More than 112,000 but fewer than 124,000', '124,000 or more']

As of 10/19 there are 75,141 cases. This means there is about 2500/week over the last two weeks. Since there are less than 5 weeks left until this question closes, if we continue to see 2500 every week, we'll see under 88,000 cases. We've nearly passed 76,000 global cases so I'm shifting my forecast to highest likelihood for # of cases to be in the second range. Most news report indicate that the number of new cases are drooping. However, this Nature article from 10/12 says that the future of Monkeypox is uncertain (potential spread in college campus, people that should be getting tested aren't, vaccines are not readily available everywhere, etc). Because of this uncertainty, I've also increased my probability of the 88K-100K range.

In recent weeks, the number of monkeypox cases reported in Europe and the Americas declined, driving the overall downward trend observed since August 2022. Last week, the WHO launched its Monkeypox Strategic Preparedness, Readiness and Response Plan which outlines the priority actions needed to stop human-to-human transmission of monkeypox,minimize animal-human transmission of the virus in affected countries, and protect vulnerable groups at risk of severe disease. I assume that this Response Plan will gradually prove effective in lowering transmission rates further. As such, the most likely option from the current baseline of ~68k infections is that infections will surpass 76k but remain below 88k, with a chance of number of infections going up to 100k people. I do not anticipate infection numbers to be much higher than 100k

As of 10/19, the number of cases reached 73,531, which is a bit more than 2,000 additional cases since last week. Since there are more than four weeks remaining, if the growth rate remains stable (it will probably slightly decrease, as seen by a slower weekly growth rate in cases two week ago compared to this week, if there is no major unfolding in this case), we should pass beyond 76,000 in two weeks. By November 21, if the growth rate remains the same, we should still be in the bandwidth between 76,000 and 88,000. So I am reducing my probability for less than 76,000 and increasing my probability between 76,000 and 88,000. I am not touching the other bands since I don't have any information stating that we are likely to see more than 88,000 cases.

If the trend of percent change continues to go down in similar ways, we might expect cumulative cases in the low 80,000s. If there is a plateau in cases, we might see cumulative cases in the low 90,000s. Articles say that there is a declining outbreak but are wary that people will become too lax (which could lead to a surge of infection. As such, I'm not ruling out some of the higher ranges.

The growth in cases is driven by USA (with the largest number, 26.9k) Brazil (8.5k), and Western Europe. These are areas where the vaccine rollout has been uneven, especially compared to the COVID-19 vaccine and its boosters. It seems very probable that the end of November there will be more cases but not at the speed of the initial months. The rate of infection has slowed, but there were still almost 15,000 reported cases over the last month. However, the rate of infection has slowed worldwide so I would be surprised to see cumulative case rates >100,000.

First, we're looking at a time period of approx 5 weeks. While cases are still increasing, the rate of increase has slowed down, with the number of cases slowly plateauing. It's possible this is driven by the fall in cases specifically in US and Europe. Over the next few weeks, I would expect cases to continue increasing at this low rate. Unless the virus mutates or people becoming more lax leads to a concentrated outbreak, I think its unlikely for cases to rise above 112,000.

As of today, we are at 71,326. Let's project forward using different rates. The 20 November is 40 days (inclusive), or 5 weeks and 5 days.Since:

The number of confirmed cases has risen by about 15,000 in the last month, but the rate of infection has been declining in the United States and Europe. On the other hand, the case rate is increasing in countries in South America and in Africa. The current number is 71,326. Looking at the world cumulative confirmed cases, the number of confirmed cases appears to be increasing at a decreasing rate. Given this information, I estimate that it is most likely that the number will be between 76,000 and 88,000 in late November.

Rates are going down in the US and EU (places that are confirming and measuring), largely a result of education and vaccination. The rates of confirmed cases are going down each week. I would estimate on average there will be about 275 new confirmed cases worldwide each week in the next month.

As of today (10/12), the cumulative number of cases is at 71,326. When we look at the log curve, it appears that the number of cases worldwide is no longer growing exponentially but rather is reaching a "plateau". Cases will still arise (especially with new variants in Congo and the UK), but the number of cases should grow more slowly than it is earlier in the pandemic. It took around 3 weeks for the number of cases to increase of 6,000 (09/24 to 10/12). And the question closes in around 5 weeks, which is twice the time that it took to increase cases by 6,000. So it is unlikely that cases will be below 76,000. But there is a high probability it will be between 76,000 and 88,000. It could go beyond 88,000 worldwide if there is a new variant that is more contagious.
The curve looks like it is plateauing, and therefore it should not have huge spikes. We can look at vaccines and awareness of MP as to less exponential increases.
Increase about 1k per week, with 4 weeks to go. Curve is also flattening, so think can only be bins1 or 2. Could be close to boundary.

If the current situation were simply projected forward, we'll very likely end up in bin 2. I'm a little concerned that we might start to see some clear cases of airborne transmission, but that probably wouldn't be noticeable until around December, if it is noticeable at all. With smallpox, the peak was around January each year, and if we're going to see anything more than a tiny percentage of cases transmitted by the airborne route, we'll likely only really notice in Dec-Jan.

From August to September, the number of cases nearly doubled, then from September to October there was a 30% increase. It looks like the curve is plateauing; in fact according to NPR, the CDC says that "cases are probably going to plateau or decline over the next few weeks and fall significantly over the next few months." At the same time monkeypox is mutating as it spreads so there could be a new variant that's more contagious.. yet since the disease spreads through very close contact and since there's been more education about monkeypox especially in the most vulnerable communities it seems like we won't see exponential growth until 11/20.
monkey pox cases have not been increasing that rapidly so the number will gradually grow but not at that fast of a pace

The last update on OWID was on the 6th of October i.e., 45 days before the 20th of November. Thus by the 20th of November, there will be 71,237+45x cases where x is the average over the next 45 days.
